00:06:11.000 --> 00:06:14.000
So the first thing we're going to talk about is embracing the blank slate.

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:19.000
If you have RStudio open, you can copy and run this snippet right now.

00:06:19.000 --> 00:06:32.000
And the blank slate is going to mean that you set RStudio up so that every time you start working, you're working in a fresh session where you're not carrying around stuff that you computed two weeks ago.

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:38.000
So this means disabling the option that will cause you to save your RStudio workspace.

00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:41.000
RStudio won't ask you to save it when you quit.

00:06:41.000 --> 00:06:43.000
It won't load it when you start.

00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:47.000
This last line is just like a sort of file hygiene thing.

00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:58.000
But embracing the blank slate, this is just going to make your life a lot easier as you prepare to start moving between different projects.

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:04.000
So that's, again, the briefest possible version of what the blank slate is about.

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:10.000
In combination with that, one of the things you want to be prepared to do is to restart your R session often.

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:15.000
If you have objects that you think are valuable, there are ways to save them.

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:17.000
You can save them as RDS files.

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:19.000
You can save them as a QS file.

00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:25.000
There's a bunch of formats you can use if you need to serialize something in particular about an R object.

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:35.000
But most of the time, what you really want to make sure you've saved is the source for how you created that R object from your raw data, which you did not modify.

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:45.000
And so being in the habit of restarting your R session is going to help you make sure that you're not carrying around stuff that you calculated weeks ago.

00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:51.000
Because that can often be the source of really confusing and difficult to debug problems.

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:59.000
And so these are the shortcuts for restarting an RStudio session or a Puzzletron session if you're in one.

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:03.000
And if you have it open, you should run it right now.

00:08:03.000 --> 00:08:10.000
And then the last thing you're going to do here is you're going to ‑‑ there are a couple of these.

00:08:10.000 --> 00:08:20.000
These two pieces of code here are often signifiers that something about your project workflow might not be quite complete.

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:35.000
This is a link to kind of the tweet that people will cite often where Jenny Bryan, the original author of this course, has threatened to set your computer on fire if you do one of these two things.

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:45.000
And the reason we don't want to do those is because if you're trying to work in a reproducible way where you're not carrying things with you between sessions,

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:54.000
then if you're running this at the beginning of a script, it's because you're hoping that this resets you to a clean state, and it doesn't.

00:08:54.000 --> 00:09:05.000
Right? So there are things you can modify about a session, like your global session options or environment variables that you set as you're computing things, and this isn't going to reset those.

00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:22.000
And similarly, if you are changing your working directory because you're trying to access files that are in different places, that computation is much less likely to be successful if you're trying to take it with you across machines.

00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:32.000
So if you have either of these things in your code, again, it's an opportunity to think about adopting that blank slate and thinking about changing that workflow.

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:45.000
One of the things that we'll cite that's particularly helpful here is the here package, which gives you a way of referencing paths relative to a project's root directory, whatever that is.

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:53.000
That might be a project where you have the RStudio project file. That might be something where there's a git directory.

00:09:53.000 --> 00:10:05.000
But using this to construct paths in your project means that you can get RStudio or R to reference files in the correct place without needing to change your working directory.

